MOB and involved in community methane oxidation. In sea ice, where methane concentrations of 82\&thinsp;{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}±{\textless}/span{\textgreater}\&thinsp;35.8\&thinsp;nmol\&thinsp;kg{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$^{\textrm{−1}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} were found, \textit{Methylobacterium} ({\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}\textit{α}{\textless}/span{\textgreater}-Proteobacteria) was the dominant MOB with a relative abundance of 80\&thinsp;\%. Total MOB abundances were very low in sea ice, with maximal fractions found at the ice–snow interface (0.1\&thinsp;\%), while non-MOB methylotrophs were present in abundances similar to natural seawater communities. The dissimilarities in MOB taxa, methane concentrations, and stable isotope ratios between the sea ice and water column point toward different methane dynamics in the two environments.{\textless}/p{\textgreater}},
