ess}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}−21.1{\textless}/span{\textgreater}\&thinsp;‰), and high {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}C∕N{\textless}/span{\textgreater} ratios (13–45), suggesting that the source of excess DOC is terrestrial C{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$_{\textrm{3}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} plants by direct land–seawater interactions. Our results show that multiple DOM tracers such as {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}\textit{δ}$^{\textrm{13}}$C{\textless}/span{\textgreater}-DOC, FDOM, and {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}C∕N{\textless}/span{\textgreater} ratios are powerful for determining different sources of DOM occurring in coastal waters.{\textless}/p{\textgreater}},
